        <a href="/world/the-rim/">Return to the Rim</a>
        <a href="/artefacts/maps/">Reader map</a>
        <a href="/language/lexicon/">Rimaeri in the lexicon</a>
      </div>
    </article>

    <article class="panel">
      <p class="eyebrow">Daily life</p>
      <h2>How Rimaeri life is learned</h2>
      <p>Children learn the Rim through ordinary tasks: watching paths, listening to weather, carrying messages, counting turns, remembering agreements, and noticing when a route feels different from the day before.</p>
      <p>Knowledge is practical. A child may learn which stones stay dry after mist, which calls mean wait, which cloth-pattern belongs to which route-house, and when a promise needs more than one witness.</p>
      <p>This makes Rimaeri childhood active without making every child heroic. Much of the learning is small, repeated, and useful.</p>
    </article>

    <article class="panel">
      <p class="eyebrow">Names</p>
      <h2>Rimaeri and Rimmers</h2>
      <p><strong>Rimaeri</strong> is the name used among the people themselves.</p>
      <p><strong>Rimmers</strong> is an outsider word. It can be ordinary, careless, affectionate, dismissive, or rude depending on who says it and why.</p>
      <p>The site should normally use Rimaeri. Use Rimmers only when the outsider point of view matters.</p>
    </article>

    <p>Routes, weather, exchange, shared knowledge, and rhythm shape daily life. Fairness and remembrance can carry as much weight as possession or fixed boundaries.</p>
    <p>Rimaeri life is varied. Families, places, duties, and ways of carrying history can differ while still holding a shared sense of belonging to the Rim.</p>
